# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: instrumentation-amplifier
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] In electronics, the **common mode rejection ratio** (**CMRR**) of a differential amplifier (or other device) is a metric used to quantify the ability of the device to reject common-mode signals, i.e. those that appear simultaneously and in-phase on both inputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] An ideal differential amplifier would have infinite CMRR, however this is not achievable in practice.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] A high CMRR is required when a differential signal must be amplified in the presence of a possibly large common-mode input, such as strong electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] An example is audio transmission over balanced line in sound reinforcement or recording.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Ideally, a differential amplifier takes the voltages, $V_{+}$ and $V_{-}$ on its two inputs and produces an output voltage $V_{\mathrm {o} }=A_{\mathrm {d} }(V_{+}-V_{-})$ , where $A_{\mathrm {d} }$ is the differential gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] where $A_{\mathrm {cm} }$ is the "common-mode gain", which is typically much smaller than the differential gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] As differential gain should exceed common-mode gain, this will be a positive number, and the higher the better.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR is a very important specification, as it indicates how much of the unwanted common-mode signal will appear in the output, typically a measurement of some quantity.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The value of the CMRR often depends on signal frequency, and must be specified as a function thereof.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] It is often important in reducing noise on transmission lines.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] For example, when measuring the voltage of a thermocouple in a noisy environment, the electrical noise from the environment appears as an offset on both input leads, making it a common-mode voltage signal.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR of the measurement instrument determines the attenuation applied to the offset or noise.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] CMRR is an important feature of operational amplifiers, difference amplifiers and instrumentation amplifiers, and can be found in the datasheet.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR often varies with the frequency of the common-mode signal, and is often much higher at higher gain settings.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The key to achieving a high CMRR is usually the use of very precisely matched resistors (better than 0.1%) to minimise any difference in the amplification of the negative and positive sides of the signal.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Single-chip instrumentation amplifiers typically have laser-trimmed resistors to achieve a CMRR in excess of 100 dB, sometimes even 130 dB.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Here, port1 is a single-ended input, and ports 2 and 3 are differential outputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR of the balun represents the smallness of the gain and phase error between the differential outputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/common-mode-rejection-ratio] If the phase difference between the differential outputs of the balun is close to 180° and the amplitudes are equal, the CMRR will be high.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] A **differential amplifier** is a type of electronic amplifier that amplifies the difference between two input voltages but suppresses any voltage common to the two inputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Single amplifiers are usually implemented by either adding the appropriate feedback resistors to a standard op-amp, or with a dedicated integrated circuit containing internal feedback resistors.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] It is also a common sub-component of larger integrated circuits handling analog signals.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In practice, however, the gain is not quite equal for the two inputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This means, for instance, that if $V_{\text{in}}^{+}$ and $V_{\text{in}}^{-}$ are equal, the output will not be zero, as it would be in the ideal case.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] where $A_{\text{c}}$ is called the common-mode gain of the amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] As differential amplifiers are often used to null out noise or bias voltages that appear at both inputs, a low common-mode gain is usually desired.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR), usually defined as the ratio between differential-mode gain and common-mode gain, indicates the ability of the amplifier to accurately cancel voltages that are common to both inputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In a perfectly symmetric differential amplifier, $A_{\text{c}}$ is zero, and the CMRR is infinite.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Note that a differential amplifier is a more general form of amplifier than one with a single input; by grounding one input of a differential amplifier, a single-ended amplifier results.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Modern differential amplifiers are usually implemented with a basic two-transistor circuit called a *“long-tailed” pair* or *differential pair*.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This circuit was originally implemented using a pair of vacuum tubes.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The circuit works the same way for all three-terminal devices with current gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The bias points of “long-tail” resistor circuit are largely determined by Ohm's law and less so by active-component characteristics.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was developed from earlier knowledge of push–pull circuit techniques and measurement bridges.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] An early circuit which closely resembles a long-tailed pair was published by British neurophysiologist Bryan Matthews in 1934, and it seems likely that this was intended to be a true long-tailed pair but was published with a drawing error.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The earliest definite long-tailed pair circuit appears in a patent submitted by Alan Blumlein in 1936.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] By the end of the 1930s the topology was well established and had been described by various authors, including Frank Offner (1937), Otto Schmitt (1937) and Jan Friedrich Toennies (1938), and it was particularly used for detection and measurement of physiological impulses.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was very successfully used in early British computing, most notably the Pilot ACE model and descendants, Maurice Wilkes’ EDSAC, and probably others designed by people who worked with Blumlein or his peers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] One disadvantage is that the output voltage swing (typically ±10–20 V) was imposed upon a high DC voltage (200 V or so), requiring care in signal coupling, usually some form of wide-band DC coupling.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Many computers of this time tried to avoid this problem by using only AC-coupled pulse logic, which made them very large and overly complex (ENIAC: 18,000 tubes for a 20-digit calculator) or unreliable.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] DC-coupled circuitry became the norm after the first generation of vacuum-tube computers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] A differential (long-tailed, emitter-coupled) pair amplifier consists of two amplifying stages with common (emitter, source or cathode) degeneration.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] With two inputs and two outputs, this forms a differential amplifier stage (Figure 2).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The two bases (or grids or gates) are inputs which are differentially amplified (subtracted and multiplied) by the transistor pair; they can be fed with a differential (balanced) input signal, or one input could be grounded to form a phase splitter circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] An amplifier with differential output can drive a floating load or another stage with differential input.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] If the differential output is not desired, then only one output can be used (taken from just one of the collectors (or anodes or drains), disregarding the other output; this configuration is referred to as *single-ended output*.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The gain is half that of the stage with differential output.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] To avoid sacrificing gain, a differential to single-ended converter can be utilized.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This is often implemented as a current mirror (Figure 3, below).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The emitter-coupled amplifier is compensated for temperature drifts, VBE is cancelled, and the Miller effect and transistor saturation are avoided.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] That is why it is used to form emitter-coupled amplifiers (avoiding Miller effect), phase splitter circuits (obtaining two inverse voltages), ECL gates and switches (avoiding transistor saturation), etc.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] To explain the circuit operation, four particular modes are isolated below although, in practice, some of them act simultaneously and their effects are superimposed.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In contrast with classic amplifying stages that are biased from the side of the base (and so they are highly β-dependent), the differential pair is directly biased from the side of the emitters by sinking/injecting the total quiescent current.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The series negative feedback (the emitter degeneration) makes the transistors act as voltage stabilizers; it forces them to adjust their VBE voltages (base currents) to pass the quiescent current through their collector-emitter junctions.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] So, due to the negative feedback, the quiescent current depends only slightly on the transistor's β.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The biasing base currents needed to evoke the quiescent collector currents usually come from the ground, pass through the input sources and enter the bases.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] So, the sources have to be galvanic (DC) to ensure paths for the biasing current and low resistive enough to not create significant voltage drops across them.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Otherwise, additional DC elements should be connected between the bases and the ground (or the positive power supply).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In common mode (the two input voltages change in the same directions), the two voltage (emitter) followers cooperate with each other working together on the common high-resistive emitter load (the "long tail").
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] They all together increase or decrease the voltage of the common emitter point (figuratively speaking, they together "pull up" or "pull down" it so that it moves).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In addition, the dynamic load "helps" them by changing its instant ohmic resistance in the same direction as the input voltages (it increases when the voltage increases and vice versa.) thus keeping up constant total resistance between the two supply rails.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] There is a full (100%) negative feedback; the two input base voltages and the emitter voltage change simultaneously while the collector currents and the total current do not change.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] As a result, the output collector voltages do not change as well.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The collector resistors can be replaced by a current mirror (the top blue section in Fig.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] 3), whose output part acts as an active load.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Thus the differential collector current signal is converted to a single-ended voltage signal without the intrinsic 50% losses, so the gain is doubled.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This is achieved by copying the input collector current from the left to the right side, where the magnitudes of the two input signals add.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] For this purpose, the input of the current mirror is connected to the left output, and the output of the current mirror is connected to the right output of the differential amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The current mirror copies the left collector current and passes it through the right transistor that produces the right collector current.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] At this right output of the differential amplifier, the two signal currents (pos. and neg. current changes) are subtracted.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In this case (differential input signal), they are equal and opposite.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Thus, the difference is twice the individual signal currents (Δ*I* − (−Δ*I*) = 2Δ*I*), and the differential to single-ended conversion is completed without gain losses.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] 4 shows the transmission characteristic of this circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The quiescent current has to be constant to ensure constant collector voltages at common mode.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This requirement is not so important in the case of a differential output, since although their two collector voltages will vary simultaneously their difference (the output voltage) will not vary.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] But in the case of a single-ended output, it is extremely important to keep a constant current since the output collector voltage will vary.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Thus the higher the resistance of the current source $R_{\text{e}}$ in the original circuit of Fig.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] 2, the lower (better) is the common-mode gain $A_{\text{c}}$ .
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The constant current needed could be produced by connecting an element (resistor) with very high resistance between the shared emitter node and the supply rail (negative for NPN and positive for PNP transistors), but that requires a high supply voltage.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] So in more sophisticated designs, an element with high differential (dynamic) resistance approximating a constant current source/sink (the bottom of Fig.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] It is usually implemented by a current mirror because of its high compliance voltage (small voltage drop across the output transistor).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] It is possible to connect a floating source between the two bases, but it is necessary to ensure paths for the biasing base currents.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In the case of galvanic source, only one resistor has to be connected between one of the bases and the ground.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The biasing current will enter directly this base and indirectly (through the input source) the other one.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] If the source is capacitive, two resistors have to be connected between the two bases and the ground to ensure different paths for the base currents.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The input impedance of the differential pair highly depends on the input mode.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] At common mode, the two parts behave as common-collector stages with high emitter loads; so, the input impedances are extremely high.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] At differential mode, they behave as common-emitter stages with grounded emitters; so, the input impedances are low.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The output impedance of the differential pair is high (especially for the improved differential pair with a current mirror as shown in Figure 3).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The common-mode input voltage can vary between the two supply rails but cannot closely reach them since some voltage drops (minimum 1 volt) have to remain across the output transistors of the two current mirrors.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] An operational amplifier, or op-amp, is a differential amplifier with very high differential-mode gain, very high input impedance, and low output impedance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] An op-amp differential amplifier can be built with predictable and stable gain by applying *negative* feedback (Figure 5).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Some kinds of differential amplifier usually include several simpler differential amplifiers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] For example, a fully differential amplifier, an instrumentation amplifier, or an isolation amplifier are often built from a combination of several op-amps.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Differential amplifiers are found in many circuits that utilize series negative feedback (op-amp follower, non-inverting amplifier, etc.), where one input is used for the input signal, the other for the feedback signal (usually implemented by operational amplifiers).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] For comparison, the old-fashioned inverting single-ended op-amps from the early 1940s could realize only parallel negative feedback by connecting additional resistor networks (an op-amp inverting amplifier is the most popular example).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] A common application is for the control of motors or servos, as well as for signal amplification applications.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In discrete electronics, a common arrangement for implementing a differential amplifier is the long-tailed pair, which is also usually found as the differential element in most op-amp integrated circuits.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] A long-tailed pair can be used as an analog multiplier with the differential voltage as one input and the biasing current as another.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] A differential amplifier is used as the input stage emitter coupled logic gates and as switch.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] When used as a switch, the "left" base/grid is used as signal input and the "right" base/grid is grounded; output is taken from the right collector/plate.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] When the input is zero or negative, the output is close to zero (but can be not saturated); when the input is positive, the output is most-positive, dynamic operation being the same as the amplifier use described above.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The differential amplifier is used in the cathode follower oscillator.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] The advantages are high impedance of the differential amplifier input and output and small phase shift between input and output.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] This application uses only one input and one output of the differential amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In case the operational amplifier's (non-ideal) input bias current or differential input impedance are a significant effect, one can select a feedback network that improves the effect of common-mode input signal and bias.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] In Figure 6, current generators model the input bias current at each terminal; *I*+b and *I*−b represent the input bias current at terminals *V*+ and *V*− respectively.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] which implies that the closed-loop gain for the differential signal is *V*+in − *V*−in, but the common-mode gain is identically zero.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] It also implies that the common-mode input bias current has cancelled out, leaving only the input offset current *I*Δb = *I*+b − *I*−b still present, and with a coefficient of *R*i.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] It is as if the input offset current is equivalent to an input offset voltage acting across an input resistance *R*i, which is the source resistance of the feedback network into the input terminals.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/differential-amplifier] Finally, as long as the open-loop voltage gain *A*ol is much larger than unity, the closed-loop voltage gain is *R*f/*R*i, the value one would obtain through the rule-of-thumb analysis known as "virtual ground".
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Additional characteristics include very low DC offset, low drift, low noise, very high open-loop gain, very high common-mode rejection ratio, and very high input impedances.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Instrumentation amplifiers are used where great accuracy and stability of the circuit both short- and long-term are required.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Although the instrumentation amplifier is usually shown schematically identical to a standard operational amplifier (op-amp), the electronic instrumentation amplifier is almost always internally composed of 3 op-amps.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] These are arranged so that there is one op-amp to buffer each input (+, −), and one to produce the desired output with adequate impedance matching for the function.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] The most commonly used instrumentation amplifier circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] The rightmost amplifier, along with the resistors labelled $R_{2}$ and $R_{3}$ is just the standard differential-amplifier circuit, with gain $R_{3}/R_{2}$ and differential input resistance $2\cdot R_{2}$ .
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] The two amplifiers on the left are the buffers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] With $R_{\text{gain}}$ removed (open-circuited), they are simple unity-gain buffers; the circuit will work in that state, with gain simply equal to $R_{3}/R_{2}$ and high input impedance because of the buffers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] This increases the common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR) of the circuit and also enables the buffers to handle much larger common-mode signals without clipping than would be the case if they were separate and had the same gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Another benefit of the method is that it boosts the gain using a single resistor rather than a pair, thus avoiding a resistor-matching problem and very conveniently allowing the gain of the circuit to be changed by changing the value of a single resistor.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] A set of switch-selectable resistors or even a potentiometer can be used for $R_{\text{gain}}$ , providing easy changes to the gain of the circuit, without the complexity of having to switch matched pairs of resistors.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] The ideal common-mode gain of an instrumentation amplifier is zero.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] In the circuit shown, common-mode gain is caused by mismatch in the resistor ratios $R_{2}/R_{3}$ and by the mismatch in common-mode gains of the two input op-amps.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Obtaining very closely matched resistors is a significant difficulty in fabricating these circuits, as is optimizing the common-mode performance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] An instrumentation amplifier can also be built with two op-amps to save on cost, but the gain must be higher than two (+6 dB).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Instrumentation amplifiers can be built with individual op-amps and precision resistors, but are also available in integrated circuit form from several manufacturers (including Texas Instruments, Analog Devices, and Renesas Electronics).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] An IC instrumentation amplifier typically contains closely matched laser-trimmed resistors, and therefore offers excellent common-mode rejection.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Instrumentation amplifiers can also be designed using "indirect current-feedback architecture", which extend the operating range of these amplifiers to the negative power supply rail, and in some cases the positive power supply rail.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] This can be particularly useful in single-supply systems, where the negative power rail is simply the circuit ground (GND).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/instrumentation-amplifier] Examples of parts utilizing this architecture are MAX4208/MAX4209 and AD8129/AD8130 Archived 11 November 2014 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] An **operational amplifier** (often **op amp**, **op-amp**, or **opamp**) is a DC-coupled electronic amplifier with a differential input, a (usually) single-ended output voltage, and an extremely high gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Its name comes from its original use of performing mathematical operations in analog computers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The **voltage-feedback opamp** (**VFOA** or **VFA**, the focus of this article) amplifies the voltage difference between its two inputs, while the less common *current-feedback op amp* (CFOA) amplifies the current between its two inputs.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] By using negative feedback, the characteristics of an op amp application circuit (e.g., its gain, input and output impedance, bandwidth, and functionality) can be determined by external components and have little dependence on temperature coefficients or engineering tolerance in the op amp itself.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] This flexibility has made the op amp a popular building block in analog circuits.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Today, op amps are used widely in consumer, industrial, and scientific electronics.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Many standard integrated circuit op amps cost only a few cents; however, some integrated or hybrid operational amplifiers with special performance specifications may cost over US$100.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Op amps may be packaged as components or used as elements of more complex integrated circuits.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The op amp is one type of differential amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The amplifier's differential inputs consist of a non-inverting input (+) with voltage *V*+ and an inverting input (−) with voltage *V*−; ideally the op amp amplifies only the difference in voltage between the two, which is called the *differential input voltage*.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output voltage of the op amp *V*out is given by the equation $V_{\text{out}}=A_{\text{OL}}(V_{+}-V_{-}),$ where *A*OL is the open-loop gain of the amplifier (the term "open-loop" refers to the absence of an external feedback loop from the output to the input).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The magnitude of *A*OL is typically very large (100,000 or more for integrated circuit op amps, corresponding to +100 dB).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Thus, even small microvolts of difference between *V*+ and *V*− may drive the amplifier into clipping or saturation.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The magnitude of *A*OL is not well controlled by the manufacturing process, and so it is impractical to use an open-loop amplifier as a stand-alone differential amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Without negative feedback, and optionally positive feedback for regeneration, an *open-loop* op amp acts as a comparator, although comparator ICs are better suited.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] If the inverting input of an ideal op amp is held at ground (0 V), and the input voltage *V*in applied to the non-inverting input is positive, the output will be maximum positive; if *V*in is negative, the output will be maximum negative.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] If predictable operation is desired, negative feedback is used by applying a portion of the output voltage to the inverting input.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The *closed-loop* feedback greatly reduces the gain of the circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] When negative feedback is used, the circuit's overall gain and response are determined primarily by the feedback network, rather than by the op-amp characteristics.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] If the feedback network is made of components with values small relative to the op amp's input impedance, the value of the op amp's open-loop response *A*OL does not seriously affect the circuit's performance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In this context, high input impedance at the input terminals and low output impedance at the output terminal(s) are particularly useful features of an op amp.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The response of the op-amp circuit with its input, output, and feedback circuits to an input is characterized mathematically by a transfer function; designing an op-amp circuit to have a desired transfer function is in the realm of electrical engineering.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The transfer functions are important in most applications of op amps, such as in analog computers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In the non-inverting amplifier on the right, the presence of negative feedback via the voltage divider *R*f, *R*g determines the *closed-loop gain* *A*CL = *V*out / *V*in.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Equilibrium will be established when *V*out is just sufficient to pull the inverting input to the same voltage as *V*in.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The voltage gain of the entire circuit is thus 1 + *R*f / *R*g.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] As a simple example, if *V*in = 1 V and Rf = *R*g, *V*out will be 2 V, exactly the amount required to keep *V*− at 1 V.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Because of the feedback provided by the *R*f, *R*g network, this is a *closed-loop* circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The input impedance of the (+) and (−) pins is much larger than other resistances in the circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The first rule only applies in the usual case where the op amp is used in a negative feedback design, where there is a signal path of some sort feeding back from the output to the inverting input.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] These rules are commonly used as a good first approximation for analyzing or designing op-amp circuits.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] None of these ideals can be perfectly realized.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] A real op amp may be modeled with non-infinite or non-zero parameters using equivalent resistors and capacitors in the op-amp model.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The designer can then include these effects in the overall performance of the final circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Some parameters may turn out to have negligible effect on the final design, while others represent actual limitations of the final performance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Real op amps differ from the ideal model in various aspects.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] is finite in real operational amplifiers.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Typical devices exhibit open-loop DC gain exceeding 100,000.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] (i.e., the product of open-loop and feedback gains) is very large, the closed-loop gain will be determined entirely by the amount of negative feedback (i.e., it will be independent of open-loop gain).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In applications where the closed-loop gain must be very high (approaching the open-loop gain), the feedback gain will be very low and the lower loop gain in these cases causes non-ideal behavior from the circuit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Low output impedance is important for low-impedance loads; for these loads, the voltage drop across the output impedance effectively reduces the open-loop gain.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In configurations with a voltage-sensing negative feedback, the output impedance of the amplifier is effectively lowered; thus, in linear applications, op-amp circuits usually exhibit a very low output impedance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] in the output stage and will dissipate more power, so low-power designs may purposely sacrifice low output impedance.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] is the impedance from each input to ground.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] can be a critical issue for high-frequency operation, where it reduces input impedance and may cause phase shifts.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] When high resistances or sources with high output impedances are used in the circuit, these small currents can produce significant voltage drops.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] inputs are matched, then those voltages at each input will be equal.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] between its inputs, these matched voltages will have no effect.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] It is more common for the input currents to be slightly mismatched.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] This offset voltage can create offsets or drift in the operational amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Input offset voltage is a voltage required across the op amp's input terminals to drive the output voltage to zero.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In the perfect amplifier, there would be no input offset voltage.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] However, it exists because of imperfections in the differential amplifier input stage of op amps.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Input offset voltage creates two problems: First, due to the amplifier's high voltage gain, it virtually assures that the amplifier output will go into saturation if it is operated without negative feedback, even when the input terminals are wired together.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Second, in a closed-loop, negative-feedback configuration, the input offset voltage is amplified along with the signal and this may pose a problem if high precision DC amplification is required or if the input signal is very small.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] A perfect operational amplifier amplifies only the voltage difference between its two inputs, completely rejecting all voltages that are common to both.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] However, the differential input stage of an operational amplifier is never perfect, leading to the amplification of these common voltages to some degree.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output of a perfect operational amplifier will be independent of power supply voltage fluctuations.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] (PSRR) that reflects how well the op amp can reject noise in its power supply from propagating to the output.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] With increasing frequency, the power-supply rejection usually gets worse.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Performance and properties of the amplifier typically change, to some extent, with changes in temperature.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Temperature drift of the input offset voltage is especially important.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Real op-amp parameters are subject to slow change over time and with changes in temperature, input conditions, etc.
