[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The circuit designer can implement this compensation externally with a separate circuit component.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] that sufficiently attenuates the high-frequency gain of the operational amplifier.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The location of this pole may be fixed internally by the manufacturer or configured by the circuit designer using methods specific to the op amp.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In general, dominant-pole frequency compensation reduces the bandwidth of the op amp even further.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] When the desired closed-loop gain is high, op-amp frequency compensation is often not needed because the requisite open-loop gain is sufficiently low; consequently, applications with high closed-loop gain can make use of op amps with higher bandwidths.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Limited bandwidth also results in lower amounts of feedback at higher frequencies, producing higher distortion, and output impedance as the frequency increases.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] , because their bandwidth doesn't decrease with gain like voltage-feedback op amps.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Amplifiers intrinsically output noise, even when there is no signal applied.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] This can be due to internal thermal noise and flicker noise of the device.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] , which is specifically designed for minimum intrinsic noise, may be required to meet performance requirements.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output of older op amps can reach to within one or two volts of the supply rails.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] can reach to within millivolts of the supply rails when providing low output currents.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] , usually specified in volts per microsecond (V/μs).
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] When slew rate limiting occurs, further increases in the input signal have no effect on the rate of change of the output.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] As a general rule, low-power and small-bandwidth op amps have low slew rates.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output voltage may not be accurately proportional to the difference between the input voltages, producing distortion.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] This effect will be very small in a practical circuit where substantial negative feedback is used.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In some integrated op amps, when the published common mode voltage is violated (e.g., by one of the inputs being driven to one of the supply voltages), the output may slew to the opposite polarity from what is expected in normal operation.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] In practice, most op amps are designed to limit the output current to prevent damage to the device, typically around 25 mA for a type 741 IC op amp.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Output voltage cannot exceed the power supply voltage supplied to the op amp.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The maximum output of most op amps is further reduced by some amount due to limitations in the output circuitry.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output sink current is the maximum current allowed to sink into the output stage.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Some manufacturers provide an output voltage vs. the output sink current plot, which gives an idea of the output voltage when it is sinking current from another source into the output pin.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The output current flows through the op amp's internal output impedance, generating heat that must be dissipated.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] If the op amp dissipates too much power, then its temperature will increase above some safe limit.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] The op amp must shut down or risk being damaged.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] op amps approximate more closely the ideal op amp than bipolar ICs when it comes to input impedance and input bias currents.
[src:instrumentation-amplifier/operational-amplifier] Generally, at room temperature, with a fairly large signal and limited bandwidth, FET and MOSFET op amps now offer better performance.
